text: This feels flat, like Disney's other live action takes such as Oz the Great and Powerful, Alice in Wonderland and Beauty and the Beast. Sure there are some fantastic visuals and gorgeous costumes--but it feels like a chocolate Easter bunny--hollow on the inside compared to the original stories. The only recent live action Disney movie that truly grabbed me so far was Christopher Robin, which worked perfectly with some simple yet adorable designs for the characters and of course Jim Cumming's excellent voice work as Tigger and Pooh. This just looks like all flash and little substance.

text: Cool idea to adapt the Nutcracker, but sadly, after Alice in Wonderland (which I also had problems with, for different reasons), this doesn't even look very original. It's like the Alice movies with a Nutcracker paint job, and I didn't like those movies because they stripped away what I liked about the original story and chained it to a weird, overly-serious war plot with a poorly handled-cliche attempt at a feminist message. This movie isn't out yet, but everything in it appears to have been done before, so I hope the movie's better and less cliche than this trailer makes it seem. I didn't spot a single original idea that hadn't been done in the last decade in a similar way.

text: I'm not sure what they're trying for.  I'll see it since I love the story of the Nutcracker ever since I was little and saw the animated 1990 "The Nutcracker Prince."  That one is based more on the book than the ballet, but they do feature Tchaikovsky's music in it.  The book's got an interesting plot, I'm not sure why Disney didn't just use the book as a base to make a live action movie and use this other idea of realms to make their own unique product.  I can see elements from the ballet more than I can from the book, but maybe it's there somewhere.  I see no evidence of the mouse king.   I guess they want the ballet's Mother Ginger to be the villain.  Weird choice.  The mouse king is so iconic.  Hopefully he'll show up somewhere.

text: I have a very NOT so jolly feeling about this movie. I first saw the Nutcracker Ballet when I was six years old with my grandmother. Ever since, it has remained a central part of my Christmas season. When I heard that it was getting made into a full length, live action film, I was very excited. I never expected this film to be EXACTLY the same as the ballet. That would have been unreasonable. What I was expecting was a well made, faithful adaptation of what is for me, a timeless Christmas story which is so closely associated with Christmas, that it could rival the story of the Birth of Christ. Then I saw these trailers. This is not the Nutcracker story. I'm confused why Disney even decided to put that word into the title, since this story being presented has almost nothing to do with the source material. Aside from a heavily distorted soundtrack and the opening setting, I could not find one reference to beloved characters such as the Nutcracker, the Mouse King, the Queen of the Suger Plum Forest, and more. The story being presented here is not the Nutcracker. At best, it's a fabricated remake of Tim Burton's Alice in Wonderland. At worst, it's a terrible Fanfiction which has no connection or faith towards its source. If this movie was being marketed as its own, COMPLETELY ORIGINAL AND SEPERATE creation, this would not upset me so much. I'm genuinely curious as to the reasoning behind this distortion. If the movie turns out good, then I'll still enjoy it. This is all my personal opinion, and my attempt to communicate my reaction and thoughts to this product.

text: 1st Trailer had me excited; this one has me worried it's going to be a complete butchering of the story. It's one thing to re-explore stories already told by Disney (Beauty and the Beast, Cinderella, etc.) but to create a brand new one with a few imported ideas, completely rehash the story & character positions and then slap the name Nutcracker on it; think I'll spend the money on the ballet instead.  Such a shame to avoid a real telling of the tale of the Nutcracker. It isn't a well known story. By the sounds of the track here, it doesn't look like they're going to go beyond Sugar-Plum Fairy from Tchaikovsky, another travesty considering the wealth of music from the Ballet. Not even a Mouse King to be seen. Is there even going to be an acknowledgement of the Russian origins of the story? Villification of Mother Ginger just so they can have a female villain?! WTF?

text: First, the Nutcracker was already perfectly realized in Tchaikovsky's ballet. The world certainly doesn't need Disney to come along and genericize the story to try and wring some more cash out of a beloved cultural institution. Second, including black actors in a thoroughly European story where all the characters in the original E.T.A. Hoffman story were white is tantamount to blackwashing.  You wouldn't cast white actors in a Japanese tale set in the 19th century, and just so for both historical and cultural reasons you don't cast black people to play white roles. How the media thinks it's wrong for a white actor like ScarJo to portray an Asian character in Ghost in the Shell, yet advocates that it's fair for a black actor like Idris Elba to portray a white character like James Bond, is beyond me.  Talk about double standards and hypocrisy.

text: Let's see ... a cute girl of good family (a child in the original version) goes to an alternate world and turns out to be a princess, and the ONLY ONE that can save that world from the tyranny of an evil queen ... Ah, Tim Burton's Alice ...! What, is it another movie? But if it has outlandish scenery and costumes, special effects that can leave you cross-eyed (and stunned), a war of good against bad (which in the original version was  the gingerbread men, led by the Nutcracker himself, against a six-headed mouse king  and his army), and in the midst of all the silly and adorable "girl who wants to live her life" we've seen a thousand times. And not to be left behind, the godfather of a nineteenth-century white girl turns out to be a politically correct African-American. Who cares about the original stories, when we got the topics repeated a million times to tell the same story, told each time with a different suit? The cinema that should be the most imaginative turns out to be the least.
